Currently this gam e supports only the Chinese Classical version of the game, but other variants of
Mahjong may be added tn the future.
Mahjong is a very simple game to learn to play but a real challenge to master. Perhaps that is what
m akes the gam e appealing to a worldwide audience. It takes skill and strategy to assemble a
winning hand, while at the s am e time predicting what tiles your opponents hold and impeding their
ability to win.
Winning Hands
A mahjong gam e contains a set of 144 tiles. Thi rteen tiles are distributed to four players sitting in
the position of east, south, west and north. Each play er then takes turns drawing from what is
l eftover from the 144 tiles. A winning hand is made up of 4 melds of three tiles and a pair of tiles
for “ey es”. This means that the winning hand is composed of fourt een tiles.
Figure 1: Set of Tiles
Melds
The mahjong set is composed of 3 suits along with honor tiles and flower tiles. The three suits are
dots, bamboos and charact ers. Each suit consists of a sequence of tiles numbered 1-9. Each number
also exists in quadruplets. To make a meld, you need to have three tiles in a sequence of the sam e
suit, or make three o f a kind in the s ame suit. Som e example melds are illustrated below in green.
For the honor tiles, they a broken down between the wind tiles and also the dragon tiles. The wind
tiles are east, south, west and north. The dragon tiles are green, red and white. Each of thes e tiles is
also in quadruplets but unlik e the suits, you can not make a meld of them in a sequence, only three
of a kind is accepted.
The flower tiles are used for bonus points but cannot be used to make a melds. If these tiles are
drawn, the play er puts the tiles in front of them. This serves as a reminder of the ext ra potential
points they accrued should they win the hand. Subsequently they redraw a new tile.

Game Play
Now that there’s a basic understanding of what constitutes a winning hand: 4 melds of 3 tiles and a
pair of the same tiles fo r a total of fourteen, it’s time to des cribe the sequen ce of pl ay.
The game officially st arts with the player sitting in the eastern spot. They st art off as the deal er with
the privilege to be passed to each player accordingly unless the dealer actually wins th e hand, in
which case they rem ain the deal er.
The dealer draws first from the “wall” of leftover tiles stacked two tiles high in front of each pl ayer.
They can choose to keep or dis card the tile but al ways keeping in mind that they need to have
thirteen tiles in their hand. If they achieve a winning hand of fourteen they can declare it
immediately and lay their hand out for all to see.
Once a tile is discarded there are several options:
• Any play er can kong:
◦ In the rare case where the tile discarded makes a 4-of-a-kind, the first player to “kong”
pi cks that tile up and lays out their 4-of-a-kind for all to see.
• Any play er can pong:
◦ In the not-so-rare case where the tile discarded makes a 3-of-a-kind, the first player to
“pong” picks that til e up and lays out th eir 4-of-a-kind for all to s ee.
• Any play er can chow:
◦ In the not-so-rare case where the tile discarded makes a sequen ce of three tiles o rder,
“chow” acts mu ch like pong.
• The pl ayer to the right (next player to draw tile) can tse:
◦ In the case where the discarded tile is useful to the pl ayer who’s turn to draw a tile is
next, they can claim the tile and place it in thei r hand.
If no player responds with any of the above respons es, the n ext player to the right is obliged to draw
a tile, add it to their hand, and then discard a tile from their hand to repeat the process. The play
always continues to the right of the person who last discarded th e tile, whether it cam e from a kong,
pong, chow, tse, or draw.
With the help from your opponents o r by luck of the draw, a winning hand is constructed. The
winning tile can come from anybody to finalize the 4 m elds of three and the pair of tiles for eyes to
total fourteen tiles.
As you can see, the concept of mahjong is simple enough but to be a good pl ayer, you need to be
aware of your tiles, as well as how others are constructing their winning hands. Wh at better way to
l earn this fas cinating gam e than to start playing!
